### Describe the problem that you experienced

The documentation about reusable validation rule functions for signal forms all use `field: any` as first argument.

### Enter the URL of the topic with the problem

https://angular.dev/guide/forms/signals/validation#reusable-validation-rules

### Describe what you were looking for in the documentation

I want to write a custom validator function for signal forms and I'd prefer type-safe code and I bet there is typing available.

`validate()` is declared as:
```typescript
declare function validate<TValue, TPathKind extends PathKind = PathKind.Root>(path: SchemaPath<TValue, SchemaPathRules.Supported, TPathKind>, logic: NoInfer<FieldValidator<TValue, TPathKind>>): void;
```

### Describe the actions that led you to experience the problem

I checked the documentation ğŸ˜

### Describe what you want to experience that would fix the problem

Maybe something like this works? Didn't check yet if those types are part of the official API.

```typescript
function url<TValue, TPathKind extends PathKind = PathKind.Root>(path: SchemaPath<TValue, SchemaPathRules.Supported, TPathKind>, options?: {message?: string}) {
  validate(field, ({value}) => {
    try {
      new URL(value());
      return null;
    } catch {
      return {
        kind: 'url',
        message: options?.message || 'Enter a valid URL',
      };
    }
  });
}
```

